  "texts": [
    "In the former case, the seller gains an option-specific revenue; in the latter case, the customer can progress to the next stage if any is left or leave the system without making a purchase.",
    "The purchase decision can be either governed by a stage-dependent choice model reflecting the fact that customers' preferences could change from stage to stage due to e.g.",
    "updated perceptions or patience waning, or by a stage-invariant choice model that is used across all stages (Liu et al. 2020; Feldman and Segev 2022).",
    "Many authors propose adjusted versions of known choice models to capture this dynamic behaviour (see e.g.",
    "Feng and Wang 2021; Flores et al. 2019)."
  ],
